Business Case: Website Modification
Documentation By G5: Ken Compass, Sanjay Yashpaul, Mike Tang, Melanie Okamuro



1.0 Introduction/Background 

For over 15 years, Dr.Scolinos has run two successful optometry retail sites near LAX. He is interested in utilizing web-presence as a means of targeting a new, larger pool of clientele as well as for creating a stronger sense of professional establishment for his business. Dr.S has previously employed the services of an out-of-state web consultancy during his initial pursuit of web-presence.


2.0 Business Objective 

Unsatisfied with the results of his previous endeavor, Dr.S now intends to revamp his website through content revisions as well as to mobilize a marketing strategy involving the application of new search-friendly keywords relevant to his practice. After interviewing personnel who possess tacit knowledge of his business, the G5 Team plans to enhance his two current websites through an extended web-presence. This will be developed by means of various techniques from pay-per-click campaigns to search optimization. As his primary business goal pertains to growth in clientele, targeting web-resources is an ideal venture as it will provide a larger pool of potential customers than his present method advertising does currently.


3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement 

Opportunity within this project lays mainly in utilization of the two existing sites as canvases for our modifications. Through interviews and research of competing practices, we may employ strong resources to the development of our own web-presence strategy. Furthermore, we may help reduce costs of advertisement by helping him to move away from paper and towards a digital medium. One such mode of digital advertising will result from the previously discussed extended web-presence. By revising the web-content and meta-tags, the site will gain greater visibility and eventually higher placement within the results of various search engines. This will then lead to increased views for the site and ultimately acquisition of new clients. Finally, pay-per-click advertisements within the site might offer an increased return on investment. 


4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints 

The two existing websites must be easily modifiable so that new content may be added/updated efficiently by the G5 team.
Better search engine visibility via enhanced web content and meta-tags will eventually yield higher placements. 
Pay-per-click advertisement will translate to an ROI eventually.  
Any web-presence strategy that involves recurring investment( for example: pay-per-click ads) must be approved by Dr.S.


5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation 

There are three options for addressing this opportunity:
Do Nothing, Continue with the traditional form of magazine /newspaper advertisement and not dwell into an internet presence.
Dr.S tries to find and employ the services of yet another web consulting company.
Leverage on the collective potential of UCI’s dedicated G5 team to finish the existing   	websites and implement a web presence strategy.
Based on the discussions with Dr.S, option 3 has been decided upon.


6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements 

A few important features of this project include:
Both websites must reflect the current up-to-date information about Dr.S’s practice including current insurance plans accepted.
The existing content of these two websites must be modified if necessary to ensure SOE friendliness.
Contact us page should notify appropriate employees in charge of responding to web based inquires regarding the practice.
Assigned tech-savvy personnel in these two practices will be instructed how to maintain the websites and the established ad-campaigns by the G5 team.


7.0 Budget Estimate 
 
UCI’s G5 team will provide free labor, but the ongoing pay-per-click ad campaigns that the G5 team will establish, will have a monthly budget of approximately $400 for both websites.


8.0 Schedule Estimate

This project is scheduled to be completed within 10 weeks.

9.0 Potential Risks

The current websites might not be easily modifiable.
The pay-per-click ad campaigns might not yield an expected ROI. 
Assigned employees of Dr.S’s practice might not maintain the established ad campaigns or modify the website appropriately in the future.
The main business risk is UCI’s G5 teams time and Dr.S’s money spent on ad campaigns that don’t yield the expected results.
